{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563967"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:07:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:07:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16921"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16921"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.46,0.01,0.02,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9611"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112845"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9611"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16921"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94883"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"358"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"7950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22690"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34651"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34669"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35672"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40213"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40222"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46382"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49705"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112845"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with severe left leg pain and fever. She sustained a small cut to her leg while gardening two days ago. She has Type 1 diabetes mellitus and is on regular insulin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears severely unwell. Her pulse rate is 128/min, blood pressure 80/45 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 39.5\u00b0C. Her left calf is erythematous, swollen, and exquisitely tender to touch. There is purple discolouration and some bullae formation around the site of the cut. There is a generalised blanching erythematous rash. Laboratory investigations reveal a white cell count of 22 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4-11) and creatinine 180 \u00b5mol/L (45-90).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surgical debridement","Intravenous meropenem, vancomycin and clindamycin","Computed tomography angiogram","Elevation and compression bandaging","Incision and drainage"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of toxic shock syndrome (STSS), likely secondary to necrotising fasciitis. The combination of severe pain out of proportion to examination findings, systemic toxicity, hypotension, and skin changes are classic features. Desquamation including over the palms and the soles is seen 1 - 2 weeks after onset of the illness. Streptococcus pyogenes and staphylococcus aureus enterotoxins are the causative organisms. In situations such as this several actions must be considered. The patient is in the Emergency Department and antibiotics will be immediately available. Wound exploration, debridement and necrosectomy will require surgical intervention and this must be done promptly. However there will be some sort of time lapse and antibiotics will be given in the interim.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous meropenem, vancomycin and clindamycin\u003C/strong\u003E should be administered immediately. The combination provides both direct antimicrobial activity and suppression of toxin production. Early antibiotic therapy is crucial in reducing mortality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical debridement \u003C/strong\u003Ewill be necessary as it is often required in necrotising fasciitis. However, stabilisation with antibiotics and fluid resuscitation should occur first as whilst an urgent surgical review is requested on the initial management plan, getting the patient to theatre for surgical debridement would not be obtained immediately.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E might be helpful in defining the extent of infection, but should not delay antibiotic administration. The diagnosis is primarily clinical in the acute setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevation and compression bandaging\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for cellulitis but is inappropriate in suspected necrotising fasciitis where it could compromise tissue perfusion further.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncision and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate as initial management and could potentially worsen tissue damage and spread infection. Formal surgical debridement in theatre is required if necrotising fasciitis is present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initial antibiotics, management includes aggressive fluid resuscitation, intensive care support, and likely surgical debridement. Intravenous immunoglobulin may be considered. The mortality rate remains high despite appropriate treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Streptococcal toxic shock syndrome presents with severe pain, fever, multi-organ dysfunction and \u0027sunburn\u0027 type rash.","Early recognition and immediate broad-spectrum antibiotics are crucial in streptococcal toxic shock syndrome."],"references":["Silva JM, Gomes Cochicho J, Carvalho E, Parente AR, Cruz Nodarse A, P\u00e1dua F. Streptococcal Toxic Shock Syndrome: A Case Report. Cureus. 2022.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9839978/","Atchade E, De Tymowski C, Grall N, Tanaka S, Montravers P. Toxic Shock Syndrome: A Literature Review. Antibiotics: Infection Diagnostics and Antimicrobial Therapy for Critical Patient. 2024.  Available at: https://www.mdpi.com/2079-6382/13/1/96"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94883"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16921"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94883"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-07T08:13:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-07T08:14:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9611"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112845"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}}